      <div xml:id="NA161-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟip peyarun talaivaṉ (ET: mīṇṭa talaimakaṉ) tērppākaṉ kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE who came back after finishung [his] work] said so that [his] charioteer would hear.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA161">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            iṟaiyu maruntoḻiṉ muṭitteṉap poṟaiya</l>
<l>            kaṇpō ṉīlañ cuṉaitoṟu malara</l>
<l>            vītā vēṅkaiya viyaṉeṭum puṟavi</l>
<l>            ṉimmeṉ paṟavai yīṇṭukiḷai yiriya</l>
<l>            neṭunteru vaṉṉa nērko ṇeṭuvaḻi </l>
<l>            yiḷaiya rēkuvaṉar parippa vaḷaiyeṉak</l>
<l>            kāntaḷ vaḷḷitaḻ kavikuḷam paṟuppat</l>
<l>            tōḷvali yāppa vīṇṭunam varaviṉaip</l>
<l>            puḷḷaṟi vuṟīiyiṉa kollō teḷḷitiṟ</l>
<l>            kātal keḻumiya nalatta ḷētil </l>
<l>            putalvaṟ kāṭṭip poykkun</l>
<l>            titalai yalkuṟ ṟēmoḻi yāṭkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Have the birds informed [her], clearly,</l>
<l rend="indent">of our coming here, so that the strength of [her] arms shall enclose [us]<note place="foot">Can this be the meaning of the strange phrase <term xml:lang="ta">tōḷvali yāppa</term>?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while the covering hoofs cut off the many petals of Malabar-lilies,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as if [they were] conches, while [our] young [attendants] on the move are</l>
<l rend="indent2">hurrying on the long way taken as straight as a long street<note place="foot">The impact of this comparison might be that, as usual, the tross is moving through the wilderness, but they are moving as straightforward as possible, as if on a real road. T.V.G. on the other hand explains <term xml:lang="ta">neṭunteri</term> to be an especially fertile place in the Thanjavur district.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">so that the gathering swarms of humming wings<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">immeṉa paṟavai</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a metaphor for bee.</note> retreat</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the wide long woodland of Vēṅkai trees spreading blossoms,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while in every mountain pool eye-like blue [lotus] flowers</l>
<l rend="indent4">on the heights(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">poṟaiya</term>: here the usual adjective in -a does not seem overly plausible. But what else could it be?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">because the monarch too has completed [his] difficult task,</l>
<l>– her of sweet words, [her] hips with beauty spots,</l>
<l rend="indent2">who is playing(?)<note place="foot">The <term xml:lang="ta">poykkum</term> here really is a puzzle, and T.V.G. explains it as playing, pointing out a parallel in NA 166.7 (where we have <term xml:lang="ta">poytal</term>, that is, another class of conjugation), but no commentary passage.</note>, showing [her] son</l>
<l rend="indent3">something strange, the good one full of love?</l>
        </lg>
